<bioghist>
<head>Biography</head>
<p>Prior to 1877, Ivoryton residents who wished to attend Congregational services travelled to the church in Centerbrook, CT. In 1877, the Ivoryton segment of the congregation began to meet at Comstock Hall (104 Main St in Ivoryton, second floor). Memorial Chapel was built in Ivoryton in 1888 by the Comstock family of Comstock, Cheney &amp; Co., the ivory processing factory and main employer of the village. The congregation remained a part of the Centerbrook church until 1898 when members voted to form a separate church and became the Ivoryton Congregational Church. The building was put up for sale in March, 2017. As of 2018, the congregation worships in space provided by the Essex Congregational Church.</p>
</bioghist>
<scopecontent>
<head>Scope and Content of Collection</head>
<p>The Ivoryton Congregational Church Collection consists primarily of written records including minutes of the church board and the Society of Church Workers (1897-1966), annual reports (1960-2018), Sunday School records (1888-1915) and church treasurer's records (1898-1944.) There are 8 boxes of photographs (1892-2016), including photographs of the original congregation members, the earliest pastors and deacons as well as many church events. Also included are documents, history and anniversary pamphlets, books, bibles, scrapbooks of church members, sheet music and hymnals, newspaper clippings. The names of Bessie Comstock, Sunday School teacher, and her sister Laura Comstock, organist, are frequently found throughout, as are names of other well-known families in Ivoryton history. The collection does not include current financial records.</p>
</scopecontent>
<arrangement>
<head>Arrangement</head>
<p>The collection is organized into two series: I: Photographs, arranged in chronological order and II: Documents, records, books and all other items.</p>
</arrangement>
